NSW gallery defends security system after theft of 17th century artwork

++++++++++++++++++

Moderator's comment:

How can one defend security when a million dollar painting has been stolen
during opening hours? There was no CCTV in the gallery, and no guard
present. There was no detection system attached to the painting, and it has
taken five days for the theft to become public. Still the director is
convinced his security system is second to none. What this director should
say is that the security system apparently has shortcomings and that
improvements will be considered. The gallery director also 'knows' it was
not inside job. He may be right, but how would he know.
According to the police it was an expert job, but a Bonham's specialist is
convinced the theft was performed by someone with mental problems.

Ton Cremers

+++++++++++++++++++++++=

 
The World Today - Thursday, 14 June , 2007  12:35:00
Reporter: Karen Barlow
ELEANOR HALL: A $1.4-million painting was lifted from the walls of a major
Sydney art gallery on the weekend and police have around 6,000 possible
suspects.

The self-portrait by 17th century Dutch master, Frans van Mieris, was taken
from a room in the Art Gallery of New South Wales on Sunday. 

Police say the theft happened within a two-and-a-half hour window and that
any one of the people attending the gallery that day may have seen something
suspicious.

The Gallery's Director Edmund Capon is adamant the theft is not an inside
job but police say they are pursuing all lines of inquiry. 

In Sydney, Karen Barlow reports.

KAREN BARLOW: Police believe the painting, called A Cavalier - Self
Portrait, was stolen sometime between 10am and 12:30pm on Sunday. 

Acting Superintendent Simon Hardman says the small 16 by 20 centimetre
artwork had to be unscrewed from the wall. 

SIMON HARDMAN: We believe that it was removed expertly from the gallery and
we're currently reviewing CCTV footage.

KAREN BARLOW: Trouble is there was no camera in the painting's room and
according to the Art Gallery of NSW Director, Edmund Capon, no security
guard. 

EDMUND CAPON: The 5-6,000 people who came to the gallery on Sunday might
just have a glimpse of something that might lead to the recovery of the
picture, that would be wonderful.

KAREN BARLOW: Mr Capon has defended the gallery's security system.

EDMUND CAPON: That any public art institution like this, with hundreds and
hundreds of works of art, vulnerable works of art on the wall every day,
one-and-a-quarter, one-and-a-half million people a year coming through
relies on public goodwill to an extraordinary extent. 

The other thing is that we are, we have a record of security, management,
organisation that is second to none. And an incident such as this is
extraordinarily rare. 

KAREN BARLOW: He is also not concerned that it has taken five days for the
theft to become public. 

EDMUND CAPON: That's not to say that nothing's been done. Monday was the
police; secondly, I was away; thirdly I had to speak to the donor; and
fourthly there's a lot of work been done in the last two days, believe me. 

KAREN BARLOW: The van Mieris artwork was a given to the gallery in 1993 by
philanthropist and former publisher, James Fairfax. 

It is one of the smallest paintings in the gallery, which may or may not
have made it a target. 

Edmund Capon is unimpressed.

EDMUND CAPON: How would you feel? It's like the loss of, if you walk home
and find a gap on your wall, that's how I feel. And I don't like gaps on the
wall. 

KAREN BARLOW: Art experts say the distinctiveness of the painting and the
publicity surrounding the theft will make it virtually impossible to resell.

Tim Goodman is the Chief Executive of the auction house, Bonhams and
Goodman.

TIM GOODMAN: It's a unique painting, it's highly specialised, it's an old
master, it's not hugely valuable in terms of major works of this period or
genre. So it is very unlikely that it's going to be offered for sale.

KAREN BARLOW: Mr Goodman says monetary gain is a most unlikely motive.

TIM GOODMAN: I suspect that it's the work of somebody who's possibly has
mental problems. Perhaps they have a vendetta against the gallery or perhaps
even the donor. Who knows? It could be any number of reasons. It might have
been the way the gentleman sitter in the picture looked at the thief.

KAREN BARLOW: The gallery's Director, Edmund Capon rejects any assertion
that any staff member could be the thief but police say they are pursuing
all lines of inquiry. 

The space where the van Mieris went missing has been rehung so there is no
gap on the gallery wall.

ELEANOR HALL: Karen Barlow reporting.

http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2007/s1951612.htm 




