Five years later, stolen violin found
By Erin Smith/ CambridgeChronicle.com
Thursday, June 14, 2007 - Updated: 12:50 PM EST

Nearly five years after Frederic Bednarz's violin was stolen from a Harvard
Square music school, police have found the $24,000 instrument. But it's
unclear if police ever plan to charge the crooks involved in the
high-profile heist. 
 
    For Bednarz, a Montreal-born violinist, the return of the pricey
19th-century violin is a case of too little, too late. 
 
    "Well, you know, it's been such a long time that I've dealt with it and
bought another violin," said Bednarz. 
 
    In 2002, Bednarz's violin was stolen from his locker in the basement of
the Longy School of Music while he was at lunch. At the time, Bednarz had
just arrived in Boston for a two-year stint as a professional studies
student at school working toward his artist diploma in chamber music
performance. Staff and musicians searched the school for days, but couldn't
find the violin, which Bednarz had borrowed from his Montreal sponsor. 
 
    Then, last November, Weston Police received a tip about the violin and
Cambridge Police recovered the stolen instrument, according to Weston Police
Chief Steven Shaw. 
 
    Investigators in Weston and Cambridge began working together on the case
when the violin was first stolen five years ago and revived the partnership
when Weston Police received the tip last year. 
 
    "It never really fell off the radar screen," said Shaw. 
 
    Police at both departments are keeping the details about the violin's
recovery under wraps. Cambridge Police are refusing to discuss the case or
say how the rare instrument was found. No one had been charged with the
theft as of this week, and it's unclear whether Cambridge Police ever plan
to make an arrest in the case. 
 
    "That's all we're going to give out," said police spokesman Frank
Pasquarello, who refused to give a reason for withholding the information. 
 
    The violin was earlier rumored to be from the 1700s, one of the rare
violins still in existence today crafted by Italian Santo Serafin. More
recently, however, experts estimated the instrument was made in Venice,
Italy, around 1800. 
 
    At the time of the theft, musicians suspected that the violin was stolen
by teens who didn't know the value of the instrument. Police and instrument
dealers had said the rare violin would be hard to sell on the open market
without drawing attention. 
 
    The insurance company has since refunded the money for the instrument,
and Bednarz bought and tried playing several instruments in past years,
finally settling on another older instrument. 
 
    "It's not exactly what I had, but I like it," said Bednarz. 
 
    The insurance company sold Bednarz's stolen violin at Tarisio auction
house last month, according to Chris Reuning, owner of Reuning & Son Violins
in Boston. 
 
    The violin sold at auction for $24,150, said Reuning, one of the
founding partners of Tarisio. 
 
    Tarisio is the world's largest auction house for stringed instruments
and sells more than 2,000 violins, violas, cellos and bows each year. 
 
    As for Bednarz, he moved back to Montreal this week to play with the
Molinari Quartet and doesn't mind that his former violin has a new owner. 
 
    Said Bednarz, "That's OK. I'm sure someone's happy." 

http://news.bostonherald.com/



