Painting 'could have fitted under clothes'


+++++++++++++++

Comment:

"FBI experience, is that approximately 80 per cent of museum theft cases of
art are inside jobs". This calls for some clarification. It should read 80%
of all cases 'that have been solved' appear to be inside jobs.

TC

+++++++++++++++++


By Katherine Danks
June 14, 2007 03:06pm

THE thief who stole a $1.4 million masterpiece from Sydney's Art Gallery of
NSW may have slipped it under a coat after unscrewing the painting from a
wall, the gallery's head admits.

The 17th century work by Dutch master Frans van Mieris, titled A Cavalier
(Self Portrait), was stolen from the busy gallery between 10am and 12.30pm
on Sunday, under the noses of security guards. 

The painting was swiftly and expertly removed from the wall on a day 6000
people passed through the building, said police Acting Superintendent Simon
Harding. 

Police have yet to rule out an inside job and authorities fear the
"extremely valuable and important" painting may already be out of the
country. 

Art Gallery of NSW director Edmund Capon said the theft was not reported to
police until Monday because staff had looked for the missing artwork in the
gallery's storage facilities. 

Security at the gallery was now being reviewed, Mr Capon said. 

But he said: "We have a record of security management and organisation that
is second to none, and an incident such as this is extraordinarily rare and
we have barely had an occasion like this in the past." 

Security footage is being reviewed but police say there were no cameras in
the small room where the painting was hung. 

Patrons do not pass through security screens when entering the building, and
no alarm was activated. 

While security guards were patrolling the gallery on Sunday, none were
stationed in the room where the theft occurred, police said. 

A Cavalier has been on exhibition at the gallery since it was donated by art
patron and philanthropist James Fairfax in 1993. 

Painted between 1657 and 1659, the work is one of the smallest paintings in
the gallery, measuring 30.7 cm by 26.7 cm, including the frame. 

Mr Capon said it was small enough to have been hidden under a person's
clothing. 

"To be honest, I could slip it under your coat ... it could have happened
that way," he told a reporter. 

Mr Capon appealed to members of the public at the gallery on Sunday to pass
on any relevant information. 

Police have interviewed gallery staff.

Robert E Goldman, special investigator with the FBI's art crime team, said
it was likely the heist was an inside job. 

"Our experience, the FBI experience, is that approximately 80 per cent of
museum theft cases of art are inside jobs - either people who work there -
people who we say 'have the keys to the kingdom'," Mr Goldman said on ABC
radio. 

Mr Goldman said the artwork would be extremely difficult to sell because
news of its theft would spread around the world very quickly. 

He said it was unlikely a ransom demand would be made by the art thieves. 

Mr Capon said the timber-framed artwork would likely be sold overseas if the
thieves were to offload it. 

"It's a fairly sort of discreet and esoteric audience I would say. One of
the things that occurs to me is this picture is pretty unsaleable," he said.

"Anybody who knows anything about van Mieris or Dutch painters, 17th century
painting, will know that painting and know it belongs in this building." 

The painting is on an oak panel and could crack if it is not kept in a
climate-controlled environment, he warned. 

Mr Capon said he felt a personal sense of loss following the theft. 

"If you walk home and find a gap on your wall, that's how I feel, and I
don't like gaps on the wall," he said. 

Customs and Interpol have been notified. 

http://www.news.com.au/



