Freedom in frame after theft
Matthew Westwood, Deputy arts editor 
June 15, 2007 

IT'S a tiny thing, measuring just 30cm by 26cm with frame, that could easily
be tucked inside a jacket or bag.
You could call it a Cavalier take-away. 

Now the painting by Frans van Mieris I, called A Cavalier (self portrait),
has become one of Australia's most wanted, after it was stolen from the Art
Gallery of NSW on Sunday. 

Whether the person who "expertly" unscrewed it from the gallery wall was a
professional art thief or a brazen amateur, we do not know. 

The heist breaches the unspoken contract between gallery and public: that
valuable and important works of art are there for all to enjoy. 

Visitors to the handsome sandstone edifice of the AGNSW, in Sydney's Domain,
enjoy its collection for free - there is no admission charge, unlike many
galleries overseas - and are generally unmolested by security staff. 

We should cherish that. 

But it's also easy to see how such a small and valuable painting became an
object of greed. 

There is no closed-circuit television in the small antechamber, part of the
James Fairfax Galleries, where the painting usually hangs. 

On Wednesday evening, when news of the theft became public, security patrols
in the area were still intermittent. 

The little gallery was roped off - a sign said "Area Closed: No Entry" - and
yet I was able to step over the rope and inspect the holes in the walls from
where the Cavalier had been removed. 

The Dutch Cavalier, insured for $1.4 million, does not have the national
resonance for Australians that, for example, Munch's The Scream has for
Norwegians. In 2004, The Scream was stolen from the Munch Museum in Oslo. 

The AGNSW's director, Edmund Capon, yesterday indicated that security could
be improved at the gallery. 

That may be necessary. But heightened security should not spoil our freedom
to enjoy the art collection that belongs to us all.

http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/



