June 15, 2007

Off-the-wall theft sparks global search for ?600,000 masterpieceBernard
Lagan in Sydney
 
Police believe that a A$1.4 million (?600,000) painting, deftly unscrewed
from a wall while Sydney?s most distinguished art gallery was filled with
visitors, may have already been transported overseas. 

They said that the canvas by Frans van Mieris, the 17th-century Dutch
master, stolen from the Art Gallery of New South Wales, was taken by an
expert. The painting went missing during the busiest day of the week at the
gallery, which attracted 6,000 visitors, and despite the constant presence
of security guards. 

The disappearance of the work, A Cavalier (Self Portrait), painted 1657-59,
was not reported to police until Monday because gallery staff believed
initially that it had been returned to storage. 

Edmund Capon, the gallery?s long-serving director, cut short a visit to
London after learning of the theft. He said that the work, which is roughly
the size of an A3 sheet of paper, could have been smuggled from the gallery
wrapped inside a coat. 

James Fairfax, a patriarch of the Australian newspaper publishing dynasty,
who donated the painting, has been told of its theft. The painting had been
exhibited at the gallery continuously since 1993. 

Mr Capon said that it would be difficult to find a buyer for the stolen
painting. He said: ?It?s rare painting. Van Mieris is a rare artist. One of
the things that occurs to me is that this picture is pretty much unsaleable.
Firstly, because it is a small audience and it is a very specialised
interest, and secondly, because it is well known. 

?Anyone who knows anything about Van Mieris or Dutch 17th-century painting
will know that painting and know that it belongs in this building.? 

The National Gallery in London and The Getty Museum in Los Angeles are among
the world?s leading institutions to hold work by Van Mieris in their
collections. 

Regarded as among the most influential of the Leiden ?fine painters?, his
work is noted for minutely proportioned subjects, a precise attention to
detail and the use of bright colours with a shiny finish. 

Van Mieris earned a great deal of money through his paintings. However, he
is known to have wasted his fortune funding a lavish lifestyle and through
poor management of his finances. 


